In this tutorial, Model 1 (One-Way ANOVA with random effects) is illustrated along with how to extract information to compute the Intra-class Correlation ICC. We also see how to use lme4 syntax.

Loading the Data

Load via the data via the .csv file. Note, factors need to be set up as the data are read in as character vectors in the case of the factors.

  sector <- as.factor(sector)

As another demonstration of aggregation bias (in this case, dis-aggregation bias) we fit a trivial “model” using OLS regression to obtain an estimate of the intercept as well as a confidence interval. We pretend that we don’t know about the variance between schools, or the dependency within schools

olsmod1 <- lm(mathach ~ 1, data = HSB)

Now we fit the One Way ANOVA with random effects. We use the syntax (1|school) which tells R that we want to model the school intercepts with a random effect.

mod1 <- lmer(mathach ~ 1 + (1|school), data = HSB)

summary(mod1)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: mathach ~ 1 + (1 | school)
##    Data: HSB
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 47116.8

Confidence Intervals

Note: the sigmas (which correspond to the tau’s in the model) are standard deviations Square them to get variance components.

Importantly, here we can “test” whether the \(\tau_{00}\) is different from zero by looking at the confidence interval for .sig01

Zero is not contained in the interval, so one can argue that there is “significant” variance at level 2. However, Zero is the boundary of the parameter space, and won’t generally be in the confidence interval. Another approach is to fit a model using generalized least squares and compare the models using a likelihood ratio test.

Another test based on \(\chi^{2}\) is defined in R&B but is not easily implemented in R

confint(mod1)
## Computing profile confidence intervals ...
##                 2.5 %    97.5 %
## .sig01       2.594729  3.315880
## .sigma       6.154803  6.361786
## (Intercept) 12.156289 13.117121

Residuals at level 1 should be normally distributed with 0 as the mean

Normal Q-Q plot should show an approximately straight diagonal line

plot(mod1)

qqnorm(residuals(mod1))

ICC

The intraclass correlation is \(\frac{\tau_{00}}{(\tau_{00}+\sigma^{2})}\)

The summary() output contains standard deviations rather than variances, so the best way to compute the ICC is to get that information directly from the model using VarCorr(), which extracts the covariance matrix.

vcov <- as.data.frame(VarCorr(mod1))

ICC <- vcov$vcov[1] / (vcov$vcov[1] + vcov$vcov[2])

ICC
## [1] 0.1803518

Plotting the distribution of intercepts (\(\beta_{0j}\)). By theory, the random effects should also be normally distributed with a mean of 0. We can plot that, or we can visualize the variance of the intercepts themselves. This requires estimating the intercepts, and is done using empirical bayes estimation: plopping in frequentist estimates for bayesian estimation.

Here are the results:

# save the intercepts
beta_0 <- coef(mod1)[["school"]][1]

boxplot(beta_0$`(Intercept)`, main = "School Intercepts", ylab = "MathAch")

hist(beta_0$`(Intercept)`, main = "School Intercepts")

Note, the mean of the intercepts DOES NOT equal the grand mean

# mean of the intercepts
mean(beta_0$`(Intercept)`)
## [1] 12.63697
# grand mean
mean(HSB$mathach)
## [1] 12.74785
